{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015G2JrZG4D4aiET2rZriDLU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1**: Storing a PASS review summary is blocked when any stored dimension finding for the same round has a FAIL verdict.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about validation logic when storing a summary. It could be a single function/method that checks existing findings before allowing a PASS summary to be stored. The failure mode is: \"does the storage layer/validation logic correctly query and cross-check findings?\" This involves module interaction between summary storage and findings storage.\n- REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network needed. An in-process fake DB or in-memory store could catch this.\n\n\n- MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the findings lookup would mask the actual failure, so I need real stored findings to verify the behavior.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM involved in this validation check.\n- MULTI-STEP: No multiple agentic steps.\n\nThis is an integration test—it requires the summary storage and findings storage modules working together with a realistic in-process store to catch the cross-module validation.\n\n**Behavior 2**: Stop-gate verdict computation reads per-dimension stored findings directly and does not rely only on hand-written summary text.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the gate's data source. It needs to verify that the gate module actually reads from findings storage rather than summary text. This is a module boundary issue—the gate module needs to be wired with real findings storage to confirm it's reading from the right source.\n- REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network needed.\n- MOCK-HIDE: I need real stored findings with FAIL status to verify the gate reads them correctly.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM involved in gate computation.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\n**Behavior 3**: Manual summary text overrides require an explicit override flag and produce an auditable warning record.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This involves the override flag check logic and warning record creation. The \"auditable warning record\" part suggests the warning needs to be stored somewhere, which points toward an integration test rather than a pure unit test.\n- REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network needed.\n- MOCK-HIDE: The warning record persistence needs to be real enough to verify it's actually auditable.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThis is Integration - I need to verify both that the override flag validation works AND that the warning record is actually stored or emitted.\n\n**Behavior 4**: After Phase 4 fixes, the review loop cannot finalize PASS unless a fresh review-agent round is executed on the updated diff.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: The review loop's state tracking needs to know whether a new review-agent round has been executed since the last fix phase.\n- REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network needed.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Even if I mock the review agent, I still need to verify the loop correctly tracks whether a fresh round was executed.\n- LLM-DEP: The review-agent round involves a real AI agent, but the behavior is really testing the loop's control flow - whether it enforces the requirement that a fresh review must happen before PASS finalization, not what the agent produces.\n- MULTI-STEP: This is a sequence: Phase 4 fix happens, the loop checks if a fresh review was executed, and if not, it blocks PASS.\n\nThe core behavior is about the loop enforcing that requirement, so I'm leaning toward Integration since it involves multi-module coordination between the fix phase and the review loop's finalization logic.\n\nNow I'm thinking through whether testing this actually needs a real LLM call. The failure mode is the loop finalizing PASS without executing a fresh review round - that's about control flow and state tracking. I could test this with a mock review agent by just verifying the loop refuses to finalize PASS if the fresh-round flag says no round has been executed. The real question is whether mocking the agent would hide a genuine failure. The original bug was that manual summary composition happened without rerunning review agents, so the issue is whether the loop enforces the requirement to re-execute the agent. I can test that enforcement with a mock - just verify that if the agent hasn't run, finalization is blocked.\n\nThe nuance here is whether the review happens on the *updated diff* specifically, but the core behavior being tested is the enforcement mechanism itself. This feels like an integration test - checking the loop's state tracking with module wiring, no real LLM needed. The workflow involves multiple steps: Phase 4 fixes, then checking if the review agent ran, then finalizing the decision. But what I'm really testing is whether the loop enforces that requirement.\n\nI can set up the state post-Phase-4 without a fresh review flag and verify it blocks PASS - that's testable at the integration level without actually running Phase 4. I'll go with Integration.\n\nFor the exhaustion behavior, I'm looking at whether review rounds hit their limit while MUST-FIX findings remain unresolved, triggering an escalation instead of PASS. This needs the flow logic wired together with the round counter and findings storage, but I can mock the findings and set the counter to max to verify the escalation outcome fires correctly - still an integration test.\n\nNow I'm working through the test level assignments. For behavior 4, the key question is whether the enforcement that a fresh review-agent round executed after the last fix actually requires a real LLM call, or if I can just check the state transition in isolation.\n\nSince the enforcement is fundamentally a state/flag check—verifying that a round ran—rather than validating what the agent produced, Integration testing should cover it. The \"on the updated diff\" concern is valid, but the behavior's core requirement is the execution itself, so I'll assign Integration as the primary level with some Workflow probability to account for end-to-end scenarios.\n\nNow I'm finalizing the probability distributions across all test levels for each behavior.\n\nFor the test descriptions, I'm sketching out concrete scenarios: one that validates the pre-condition by attempting to store a PASS summary when a FAIL finding exists in the same round, and another that checks whether the gate reads from actual findings rather than summary text when computing verdicts.\n\nThen I need to verify the override mechanism works correctly—rejecting manual overrides without the flag but allowing them with the flag and generating a warning record. I'm also planning a test that ensures the loop can't finalize if there's no recorded review-agent execution, and another that confirms escalation happens when MUST-FIX findings exist at the round limit.\n\nNow I'm checking whether these are truly integration tests by verifying they require multiple modules working together.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9584,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9584},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2c77238f-da6a-47b7-9961-0c1d432defcd","uuid":"c7ae50f8-009e-4dc1-8817-169832752f4e"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015G2JrZG4D4aiET2rZriDLU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01V5NPSnHUqGNt8LrY1NjKpB","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Storing a PASS review summary is blocked when any stored dimension finding for the same round has a FAIL verdict.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is a cross-module data consistency check — the summary storage layer must query the findings storage layer for the same round before accepting a PASS verdict. This boundary only exists when both modules are wired together with shared state; a unit test of either module alone cannot expose the missing cross-check. REAL-INFRA: No OS or network dependency; an in-process fake or real local store is sufficient. LLM-DEP: No AI/ML output involved. MULTI-STEP: No multi-agent chain. REJECTION-GATE: A higher level (Agentic/Workflow) is disqualified because correctness depends entirely on stored structured verdicts, not on LLM judgment.","test_description":"Seed a round's findings store with at least one dimension finding carrying a FAIL verdict. Attempt to write a PASS summary for the same round ID. Assert the write is rejected with an appropriate error. Then replace all dimension findings with PASS verdicts and retry — assert the PASS summary is now accepted. Both the findings store and the summary store must be real (or realistic in-process fakes) so the cross-check actually executes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Stop-gate verdict computation reads per-dimension stored findings directly and does not rely only on hand-written summary text.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The bug in the issue is precisely that the gate read the summary text instead of stored findings. Verifying the gate reads the correct data source requires wiring the gate module to both the findings store and the summary store with contradictory data — a unit test of the gate function alone cannot surface this if the data-source selection is inside the wiring. REAL-INFRA: No OS or network required; in-process stores suffice. LLM-DEP: Gate verdict computation is deterministic logic over structured data. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the findings store would bypass the exact integration point under test. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic/Workflow disqualified because gate computation is deterministic once data is retrieved.","test_description":"Write conflicting state into the store: store dimension findings all marked FAIL for round R, then write a summary for round R with text claiming PASS. Invoke the gate's verdict computation for round R. Assert the computed verdict is FAIL. This proves the gate consumed findings, not the summary text. The test must use real or stub-but-injected storage backends so the data-source selection path executes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.77,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Manual summary text overrides require an explicit override flag and produce an auditable warning record.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: 'Auditable warning record' means the warning must be persisted or emitted to a real store/log sink — not just returned from a function. The failure mode (silent override without audit trail) only appears when the validation logic and the audit-record sink are wired together. A unit test that stubs the sink cannot confirm the record is actually written. REAL-INFRA: No OS or network required; a local in-process record store is sufficient. LLM-DEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: System and above are disqualified — no real network, subprocess, or LLM judgment is involved.","test_description":"Attempt a manual summary override without the override flag set — assert the operation is rejected. Then attempt with the flag set — assert the override is accepted AND exactly one warning record is stored in the audit sink with fields identifying the round, the actor, and the override reason. Both the override validation logic and the audit-record sink must be real (or realistic in-process fakes).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"After Phase 4 fixes, the review loop cannot finalize PASS unless a fresh review-agent round is executed on the updated diff.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is the loop's enforcement of a state precondition: 'a fresh review-agent round must be recorded after the last fix phase before PASS finalization is allowed.' This is a loop-state × finalization-logic module boundary. The review-agent itself doesn't need to be real for this enforcement check — a stub agent that records execution is sufficient to verify the loop's guard. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network required. LLM-DEP: The enforcement check is deterministic (was a round recorded? yes/no); correctness does not depend on what the review agent produced. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the agent is safe here because behavior 4 tests the loop's precondition guard, not review quality. MULTI-STEP: While the full pipeline is multi-step, the specific failure boundary (loop blocks finalization without fresh round) can be isolated by setting loop state to 'post-Phase-4, no fresh round recorded' without running all prior phases. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow disqualified because the enforcement check does not require executing the full multi-phase pipeline; the state can be injected directly.","test_description":"Set loop state to reflect: Phase 4 fix applied, no subsequent review-agent execution recorded. Invoke the finalization path. Assert it is blocked (returns an error or pending status, not PASS). Then record a stub review-agent round execution against the updated diff token. Invoke finalization again. Assert it proceeds. No real LLM call is needed — a stub that records 'round executed on diff D' is sufficient to exercise the loop guard.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.52,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.08,"Workflow":0.3}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"If review rounds are exhausted with unresolved MUST-FIX findings, the flow emits an escalation outcome instead of PASS.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: This requires the flow's termination logic to be wired with the findings store and the round counter — three modules. A unit test of the termination function alone cannot verify that the round counter and findings query are correctly integrated. REAL-INFRA: No OS or network required. LLM-DEP: MUST-FIX findings are structured records, not LLM outputs; seeding synthetic findings is sufficient. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the findings store and counter is safe because correctness depends on the flow reading them correctly, not on their content being AI-generated. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic/Workflow disqualified — the escalation logic is deterministic over stored structured data.","test_description":"Seed the findings store with one or more MUST-FIX findings for round R. Set the round counter to its configured maximum. Invoke the flow's termination/finalization path for round R. Assert the emitted outcome is escalation (not PASS or FAIL-and-retry). Then repeat with zero MUST-FIX findings at max rounds — assert no escalation. Both the findings store and the round counter must be real (or realistic in-process fakes) so the termination logic executes end-to-end.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.76,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.06}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9584,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9584},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2c77238f-da6a-47b7-9961-0c1d432defcd","uuid":"b518c1e5-29c3-4198-a8ca-ddd3b83213da"}
